sentences: Grażyna Bacewicz ([ɡraˈʐɨna baˈt͡sɛvit͡ʂ] (listen); 5 February 1909 – 17 January 1969) was a Polish composer and violinist.
She is the second Polish female composer to have achieved national and international recognition, the first being Maria Szymanowska in the early 19th century.

In 1928 she began studying at the Warsaw Conservatory, where she studied violin with Józef Jarzębski and piano with Józef Turczyński, and composition with Kazimierz Sikorski, graduating in 1932 as a violinist and composer.

In 1928 she began studying at the Warsaw Conservatory, where she studied violin with Józef Jarzębski and piano with Józef Turczyński, and composition with Kazimierz Sikorski, graduating in 1932 as a violinist and composer.

She continued her education in Paris, having been granted a stipend by Ignacy Jan Paderewski to attend the École Normale de Musique, and studied there in 1932–33 with Nadia Boulanger (composition) and André Touret (violin).

She continued her education in Paris, having been granted a stipend by Ignacy Jan Paderewski to attend the École Normale de Musique, and studied there in 1932–33 with Nadia Boulanger (composition) and André Touret (violin).
She returned briefly to Poland to teach in Łódź, but returned to Paris in 1934 in order to study with the Hungarian violinist Carl Flesch.
From 1936 to 1938 she was the principal violinist of the Polish Radio Orchestra, which was directed then by Grzegorz Fitelberg.
She was married in 1936, and in 1942 gave birth to a daughter, Alina Biernacka, a recognized painter.
She was married in 1936, and in 1942 gave birth to a daughter, Alina Biernacka, a recognized painter.
Composition finally became her only occupation from 1954, the year in which she suffered serious injuries in a car accident.
Composition finally became her only occupation from 1954, the year in which she suffered serious injuries in a car accident.
She died of a heart attack in 1969 in Warsaw.

Among them are seven violin concertos, five sonatas for violin with piano, three for violin solo (including an early, unnumbered one from 1929), a Quartet for four violins, seven string quartets, and two piano quintets.
Her orchestral works include four numbered symphonies (1945, 1951, 1952, and 1953), a Symphony for Strings (1946), and two early symphonies, now lost.
